Source: biography by Cora McDonald Wathen   Apparently William was born out of wedlock to Ann GILES and kept her surname.  Note: There was no marriage of John Paling (William's biological father)and Ann Giles. Ann worked for the noble John Paling. Ann gave son William her maiden name of Giles as she was not married. Elizabeth Giles, Ann Giles' sister, also had a son, Thomas Giles, while working for Paling. Not being married to Paling, Elizabeth gave Thomas her maiden name of Giles.  Conquerors of the West: Stalwart Mormon Pioneers, volume 2  Name: William Giles Birth Date: 01 Jan 1797 Birth Place: Gunerson, near London, England Death Date: 07 Dec 1874 Death Place: Heber, Utah Arrival: 15 Aug 1856 Spouse: Sarah Huskinson Marriage Date: 1820 Marriage Place: of Bridgeford, England Spouse's Death Date: 05 Sep 1867 Spouse's Death Place: Provo, Utah Married 2nd: Mary Ann Day . Died: 5 Dec 1874 , Heber, Utah William and his family were baptized in 1840 . He and his sons were brick masons by trade. As they were preparing to leave for America in 1854 , a message came to William saying they had to be in Liverpool in 24 hours as the ship would sail. They sent the children on ahead saying they would quickly follow. The ship sailed without them and some others, but a smaller ship soon followed and brought the rest of the saints to the ship. There were some problems upon their arrival but soon they were able to leave for the Valley and arrived in 1856 . Some of their family remained in Quincy, Illinois, to find employment while the others went on to Burlington, Iowa . In two years they all came together and started west. Upon their arrival in the Valley, they moved on to Provo . By 1874, he had moved to Heber City, where he died. Children of 1st wife:Thomas , b. 6 Aug 1821 . Md. 1st, Susanna Moore . Md. 2nd, Jane Taylor .George , b. 19 May 1823 , Md. Mary Greenwood . Elizabeth , b. 11 Apr 1826. Md. Thomas Rasband . Ann , b. 28 Sep 1828 . D. 24 Sep 1835 . John , b.26 Jun 1831 . Md. Elizabeth Giles . Mary , b. 13 Apr 1833 . Md. John Crook . Fredrick , b. 3 Mar 1835 . Md. 1st, Mary Ann Moulton . Md. 2nd,Maria Sharp . Md. 3rd, Hannah Roberts . Emily Ann , b. 6 Jan 1837 . Md.James Carlile . Keziah , b. 20 May 1840 . Md. Charles Negus Carroll .William , b. 26 Mar 1843 . Md. Christiana Carlile . Ralph Carlile

William Giles was born in Gunerson, near Lowdham, England on 31 December 1796 to Ann Giles and John Palin.  He married Sarah Huskinson in Bridgeford, Nottingham, England in 1820.  They were the parents of ten children.  They joined the Mormon Church in the late 1840's and early 1850's and prepared to gather to Zion.  They left Liverpool and sailed to America with their family on the ship "Old England" . They arrived at New Orleans after 52 days at sea.   They met their daughter, Elizabetih Giles Rasband, and other family members in St. Louis and shortly after they went to Iowa and prepared to cross the plains.  They left  Council Bluffs on the 5th of June where they commenced their journey to Zion.  They arrived in the Salt Lake valley in 5 August 1856 and moved to Provo soon after.  Due to the hardships and exposure, his wife, Sarah,  died soon after in Provo, Utah,  a long way from her home in England.  She is buried in the Provo Cemetery.  Two years later he moved his family to the Heber valley.  They built their home in the Spring of 1860 in Fort Heber where the land had to be cleared and logs hewn for homes and buildings.  Later he married Mary Ann Day in Heber.  He died in Heber, Utah on 15 December 1874 at the age of 78, just ten days after his wife, Mary Ann died.  they are buried in the Heber City cemetery.  William and Sarah raised a fine family, all pioneers who played a part in the early settlement of Heber.

facts.value: Sarah Huskinson was born 13 April 1800 in Bridgeford, Knottingham, England to Thomas Huskinson and Elizabeth Peck. She married William Giles in 1820 when she was 20 years old.  She was the mother of ten children.  They were converted to the restored gospel and were baptized into the Mormon Church in the late 1840's in England.  They left Liverpool and sailed to America in 1854 on the ship "Old England".  They arrived at New Orleans after about 53 days on the ocean.  William and Sarah and their family and many other Saints boarded the steamboat "St. Nicholes"  and sailed up the Mississippi River as far as St. Louis.  They were examined by a doctor before they could go ashore.  The doctor and the captain quarantined all the Mormon passengers.  They had to wash all their clothing and their belongings before they could enter the city.  Two days later they were allowed to enter the city of St. Louis.  They were met there by their daughter, Elizabeth Giles Rasband,  and her family and their son, George, and his family who had come to America a few years before.  They left for Quincy where Elizabeth was living.  In two years all of the Giles family made preparations to cross the plains to Utah.  They traveled to Council Bluffs and on  5 June 1856 they commenced their journey to Zion.  They arrived in the Salt Lake valley on 15 August 1856 and they settled in Provo, Utah.  Sarah died in   Provo one  year later on 5 September 1857 from the hardships and exposure of their journey.   She was 57 years old.  She was buried in the Provo cemetery a long way from her home in England.  William settled in the Heber valley with his children and his new wife, Mary Ann Day.  They built their homes in Fort Heber in the Spring of  1860.  He died 15 December 1874 in Heber and was buried in the Heber City cemetery.  William and Sarah raised a fine family, all pioneers, who played a part in the early settlement of Heber..
